orn February 25, 1978) is an American attorney and politician from [[Orlando, Florida]], who is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[Florida's 9th congressional district|Florida's 9th district]]. He defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Wayne Liebnitzky in the 2016 general election, 57-43%.<ref name=\"first\">[http://www.latina.com/lifestyle/politics/darren-soto-first-puerto-rican-represent-florida-congress Finally! Darren Soto makes history as the first Puerto Rican to represent Florida in the U.S. Congress], ''[[Latina(magazine)|Latina]]'', BY Raquel Reichard, November 11, 2016. Retrieved November 13, 2016.</ref> Prior to being elected to Congress, Soto served for four years in the [[Florida Senate]] and five in the [[Florida House of Representatives]], representing parts of the Orlando area.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSoto was born in the borough of [[Ringwood, New Jersey]], to a [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] father, O. Lou Soto, and an [[Italian-American]] mother, Jean Soto. From 1998 to 2001, he worked for [[Prudential Insurance]] in finance while he attended college. He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Rutgers University]] in 2000, a [[Juris Doctor]] from  [[George Washington University]] in 2004, and opened his law practice the following year.\n\nSoto has a bachelor's degree in economics, and attended law school at George Washington University. In 2006, he was named class counsel in the federal class action brought on behalf of Hispanic voters against the City of Kissimmee in the U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Florida.\n\nSoto is a former member of the Civil Service Board for the City of Orlando. He served as the Treasurer of the Orange County Democrats and the Vice President of Communications for the Orange County Young Democrats (YD's). He was also the YD Co-Host for their Speak Easy events that provide a monthly forum for local and state leaders to speak to young voters.\n\n\"My family's history is the Puerto Rican history in Florida,\" Soto has said.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Delgado |first1=Jos\u00e9 A. |title=Darren Soto: \"My Family is the Puerto Rican History in Florida\" |url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/english/english/nota/darrensotomyfamilyisthepuertoricanhistoryinflorida-2230830/ |website=El Nuevo D\u00eda |accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Florida House of Representatives==\nIn 2006, Soto ran for the [[Florida House of Representatives]] from the 40th District, unsuccessfully challenging incumbent [[Andy Gardiner]]. In April 2007, he emerged victorious from a crowded [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary in a special election to replace [[John Qui\u00f1ones (politician)|John Quinones]], who had resigned to run for the [[Osceola County, Florida|Osceola County]] Commission.<ref>{{cite news |title= 6 Democrats vie for Quinones' seat: Winner of March 20 primary faces GOP's Suarez in April |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2007-03-11/news/O49DISTRICT11_1_mcmanus-osceola-county-district-49 |publisher=Orlando Sentinel|accessdate=May 17, 2013}}</ref> In the general election, Soto defeated Tony Suarez, the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee, by 285 votes. Soto was overwhelmingly re-elected in 2008 and 2010.<ref>[https://ballotpedia.org/Florida_House_of_Representatives_elections,_2008 \"Florida House of Representatives elections for 2008\"], Ballotpedia</ref><ref>[https://ballotpedia.org/Florida_House_of_Representatives_elections,_2010 \"Florida House of Representatives elections for 2010\"], Ballotpedia</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\nDuring his three terms in the Florida House, Soto supported laws to curb illegal street racing,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myfloridahouse.gov/Sections/Bills/billsdetail.aspx?BillId=42216 |title=Florida House of Representatives - CS/HB 97 - Street Racing|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> protect families of deceased firefighters, and maintain school safety. He fought to protect homeowners' access to the courts in foreclosure proceedings and to assure adequate funding to address the unprecedented housing crisis in Florida. Soto was a key voice in securing the passage of Sunrail to bring commuter rail to Central Florida.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n==Florida Senate==\nIn 2012, [[Florida Senate]] districts were redrawn, and Soto opted not to run for re-election in the House but instead to run for the newly created 14th District, which included predominantly Latino areas of [[Orange County, Florida|Orange]], [[Osceola County, Florida|Osceola]], and [[Polk County, Florida|Polk Counties]]. He won his party's nomination uncontested and faced [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Will McBride.<ref>{{cite news |title= Senate District 8 Leaning Toward Darren Soto |url=http://www.sunshinestatenews.com/story/senate-district-8-leaning-toward-darren-soto |publisher=Sunshine State News|accessdate=May 17, 2013}}</ref> Soto defeated McBride with over 70% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |title= For State Senate Districts 12, 13, 14 we endorse... |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2012-10-02/opinion/os-ed-endorse-senate-orange-100212-20121001_1_senate-district-andy-gardiner-darren-soto |publisher=Orlando Sentinel |accessdate=May 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his first term in the Florida Senate in 2013, Soto played a major role in the passage of legislation that would have expedited driver's license access for DREAMers, but it was ultimately vetoed by Governor Rick Scott,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2013/0986 |title=Senate Bill 0986 (2013) - The Florida Senate|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> setting off statewide protests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tampa.cbslocal.com/2014/07/14/protesters-want-florida-to-allow-illegal-immigrants-to-obtain-drivers-licenses/|title=Protesters Want Florida To Allow Illegal Immigrants To Obtain Driver\u2019s Licenses \u00ab CBS Tampa|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> He also played a critical role in reducing the statute of limitations from 5 years to 1 year for banks to collect foreclosure debt and helped establish Florida's Hardest Hit Principal Reduction Program. He unsuccessfully proposed an amendment that would \"raise the required jury vote from seven to 10 for death penalties.\"<ref>{{cite news |title= Timely Justice Act, Measure Speeding Up Executions, Approved By Florida Senate |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/29/timely-justice-act_n_3180168.html |publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=May 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Soto passed legislation answering the Florida Supreme Court's call to give it the authority to admit immigrant lawyers to the Florida Bar. He also strongly advocated legislation giving DREAMers in-state college tuition. He secured the initial state funding to establish a Poinciana Valencia Campus and to initiate the Lake Toho Restoration, which will clean water flowing through the Northern Everglades. In addition, he led the Democratic House and Senate Caucuses in drafting a Congressional Map during the 2014 Special Session on Redistricting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://flsenate.gov/Session/Redistricting/Plan/S014C9040 |title=S014C9040 - The Florida Senate|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2015 legislative session, Soto was fundamental in securing $11.9M in funding for Valencia College's Poinciana campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.valenciacollege.edu/about-valencia/sen-soto-rep-la-rosa-announce-11-9-million-for-poinciana-campus/|title=Sen. Soto, Rep. La Rosa Announce $11.9 Million for Poinciana Campus|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> Soto also successfully pushed for $20M to restore the [[Kissimmee River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.saintpetersblog.com/archives/222830 |title=Nancy Watkins will not run for the Tampa HD 60 seat|author=Mitch Perry|work=SaintPetersBlog |accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> This earned him the \"Champion of the Everglades\" award from the Audubon Society of Florida.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orlando-politics.com/2015/10/25/darren-soto-named-champion-of-the-everglades/|title=Darren Soto named \"Champion of the Everglades\"|date=October 25, 2015|website=The Orlando Political Observer |accessdate=June 24, 2016}}</ref> Soto also proposed legislation to ban fracking in Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2015/0166|title=Senate Bill 0166 (2015) - The Florida Senate |accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> He secured $10M in Florida's budget to promote economic growth in Osceola County for a new facility to manufacture high-tech sensors. However, the project was vetoed by Governor Rick Scott.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mynews13.com/content/news/cfnews13/news/article.html/content/news/articles/cfn/2015/6/24/gov_scott_s_veto_hur.html|title=Gov. Scott's veto hurts new research center in Osceola County |accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> Soto also introduced a bill to boost minimum teacher pay to $50,000 per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2015/0280|title=Senate Bill 0280 (2015) - The Florida Senate|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://flsenate.gov/Session/Bills/2016?chamber=senate&searchOnlyCurrentVersion=True&isIncludeAmendments=False&isFirstReference=True&filedBy=M_5108&citationType=FL%20Statutes&pageNumber=0|title=Bill List - The Florida Senate |accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSenator Soto steered funding to his district, including $15M for the UCF Sensors Manufacturing Center, $12M to complete the construction of the Poinciana Valencia College campus,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.valenciacollege.edu/about-valencia/green-issues-and-construction/gov-scott-approves-12-1-million-for-poinciana-campus/|title=Gov. Scott Approves $12.1 Million for Poinciana Campus|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> $4M in supplemental school construction money,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aroundosceola.com/osceola-projects-escape-scotts-veto-pen/|title=Official community newspaper of Kissimmee, Osceola County including Kissimmee, St. Cloud, Celebration, Poinciana, Harmony and surrounding areas|work=Osceola News-Gazette|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> $750k for the Northern Everglades and Lake Toho initiatives and $150k for a transition house that offers temporary housing for veterans. In 2016, Soto supported Chloe's Law to construct barriers around water bodies adjacent to state roads,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://knightnews.com/2016/03/chloes-law-a-bill-filed-in-memory-of-a-ucf-student-passes-florida-house-senate/|title=KnightNews.com \u00bb Chloe\u2019s Law, a bill filed in memory of a UCF student, passes Florida House & Senate|work=knightnews.com|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> the Deaf Floridian's ID bill,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.wfsu.org/post/bills-filed-help-deaf-floridians-who-may-face-arrest|title=Bills Filed To Help Deaf Floridians Who May Face Arrest|author=Sascha Cordner|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref> and the Juvenile Clean Slate bill which automatically seals misdemeanor records for juveniles who reach 21 years of age and do not reoffend as adults.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fox35orlando.com/news/politics/91714286-story|title=Clean slate for juveniles bill moving forward|author=FOX|work=WOFL|accessdate=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n====2016====\nSoto won the Democratic nomination to succeed Rep. [[Alan Grayson]], who had stepped down to run in the primary for U.S. Senate in Florida's 9th congressional district.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myfoxorlando.com/story/29568134/state-sen-darren-soto-running-for-congress |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 19, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722021137/http://www.myfoxorlando.com/story/29568134/state-sen-darren-soto-running-for-congress |archivedate=July 22, 2015}}</ref> Soto earned 36% of the vote in a four-way primary election.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/florida|title=Florida Election Results 2016 |date=August 1, 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The district is Democratic-leaning and contains all of Osceola County and parts of Orange and Polk counties. Soto has represented the majority of this district while serving in the Florida House of Representatives and the Florida Senate. The Orlando Sentinel endorsed him in his primary race, calling him an \"effective lawmaker.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/opinion/os-ed-endorsements-congressional-20160813-story.html|title=Darren Soto, Val Demings: Our picks for Congress: Endorsements 2016|first=Orlando|last=Sentinel|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref> Soto won the general election for the seat, defeating Republican Wayne Liebnitzky, 57-43%.<ref name=\"first\"/>\n\n====2018====\nSoto successfully defeated his predecessor, Alan Grayson, with a 32% margin of victory.<ref>{{cite web|author=By $${element.Contributor} |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/floridas-darren-soto-easily-holds-off-alan-grayson-comeback-bid |title=Florida\u2019s Darren Soto Easily Holds Off Alan Grayson Comeback Bid |publisher=Rollcall.com |date=August 28, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Soto received endorsements from almost every Democratic organization in his reelection campaign: National Organization for Women,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-soto-now-endorsement-20180808-story.html |title=National Organization for Women endorses U.S. Rep. Darren Soto |publisher=Orlando Sentinel |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Pride Fund to End Gun Violence,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-pride-fund-soto-demings-smith-20180802-story.html |title=Pride Fund endorses Darren Soto, Val Demings, Carlos Guillermo Smith |publisher=Orlando Sentinel |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Giffords PAC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/270318-giffords-endorses-darren-soto-in-cd-9-race |title=Giffords PAC endorses Darren Soto in CD 9 race |publisher=Florida Politics |date=July 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Democratic Environmental Caucus of Florida,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/269691-darren-soto-picks-up-democratic-environmental-caucus-of-florida-nod |title=Darren Soto picks up Democratic Environmental Caucus of Florida nod |publisher=Florida Politics |date=July 24, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> National Committee to Preserve Social Security & Medicare,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-alan-grayson-darren-soto-20180501-story.html |title=Alan Grayson returns to seek old seat in Congress |publisher=Orlando Sentinel |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Equality PAC,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lgbtequalitypac.org/equality-pac-endorses-rep-darren-soto-fl-09/ |title=Equality PAC Endorses Rep. Darren Soto (FL-09) - Equality PAC |publisher=Lgbtequalitypac.org |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> League of Conservation Voters,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-soto-conservation-voters-20180626-story.html |title=League of Conservation Voters endorses Darren Soto |publisher=Orlando Sentinel |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Human Rights Campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/266744-darren-soto-picks-up-human-rights-campaign-endorsement-in-cd-9-race |title=Darren Soto picks up Human Rights Campaign endorsement in CD 9 race |publisher=Florida Politics |date=June 19, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Florida AFL-CIO,<ref>http://flaflcio.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/2018-Florida-AFL-CIO-Endorsements.xlsx</ref> Florida Young Democrats,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orlando-rising.com/florida-young-dems-endorse-sean-shaw-jeremy-ring-darren-soto-val-demings/ |title=Florida Young Dems endorse Sean Shaw, Jeremy Ring, Darren Soto, Val Demings |publisher=Orlando Rising |date=May 15, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Orlando Professional Fire Fighters International Association of Fire Fighters Local 1365, Central Florida Police Benevolent Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/265463-darren-soto-picks-up-nods-from-fire-fighters-police-unions |title=Darren Soto picks up nods from fire fighters, police unions |publisher=Florida Politics |date=June 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Florida LGBTA Democratic Caucus,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.floridalgbtademocrats.org/ |title=Florida LGBTA Democratic Caucus |publisher=Floridalgbtademocrats.org |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> eMgage PAC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emgagepac.org/endorsees/darren-soto-democrat-9th-congressional-district/ |title=The policy home for American Muslims |publisher=Emgage PAC |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Congressional Progressive Caucus PAC,<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://westorlandonews.com/progressive-caucus-endorses-soto/ |title=Progressive Caucus Endorses Soto \u2013 WON |publisher=Westorlandonews.com |date=March 8, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> and Planned Parenthood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/263721-planned-parenthood-backs-darren-soto-in-cd-9-primary |title=Planned Parenthood backs Darren Soto in CD 9 primary |publisher=Florida Politics |date=May 15, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Soto also has the backing of Vice President Joe Biden,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/florida/story/2018/05/29/biden-endorses-soto-over-grayson-in-florida-congressional-primary-439387 |title=Biden endorses Soto over Grayson in Florida congressional primary |publisher=Politico.com |date=May 29, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Congressman John Lewis,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/263981-darren-soto-picks-up-endorsement-from-u-s-rep-john-lewis |title=Darren Soto picks up endorsement from U.S. Rep. John Lewis |publisher=Florida Politics |date=May 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> Congresswoman Linda Sanchez, Florida State Senator Vic Torres, along with every Florida Democratic Member of Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/259158-darren-sotos-campaign-announces-endorsements-10-florida-congress-members |title=Darren Soto endorsed by 10 other members of Fla. congressional district |publisher=Florida Politics |date=March 16, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCongressman Soto will face Republican candidate Wayne Liebnitzky in the general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dos.elections.myflorida.com/candidates/CanList.asp |title=Candidates and Races - Candidate Tracking system - Florida Division of Elections - Department of State |publisher=Dos.elections.myflorida.com |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===115th Congress (2017-2018)===\n===Tenure===\nSoto is the first Congressman of Puerto Rican descent elected from Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/darren-soto-elected-first-puerto-rican-congressman-florida-n680741|title=Darren Soto elected first Puerto Rican congressman from Florida |accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> In his first few weeks, Soto was named by Nancy Pelosi as one of only three freshmen Members to the Democratic Steering and Policy Committee. He was also named co-chair of the House Democratic Caucus New Economy Task Force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/244836-darren-soto-named-congressional-democrats-jobs-task-force|title=Darren Soto named to Congressional Democrats' jobs task force - Florida Politics |website=floridapolitics.com}}</ref>\n\nOn December 23, 2017, Soto passed his second bill the \"Foreign Spill Protection Act\" along with co-introducer US Rep. [[Carlos Curbelo]]. The bill eliminates a $1 Billion cap on damages for foreign oil drillers, whose oil spills pollute America\u2019s waters, to better protect Florida\u2019s beautiful coasts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/carlos-curbelos-darren-sotos-foreign-spill-protection-act-signed-law|title=Carlos Curbelo's, Darren Soto's Foreign Spill Protection Act Signed into Law|date=December 13, 2017|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSoto introduced a bill to rename a Kissimmee Post Office (HR 4042) at 1415 West Oak St after the Borinqueneers. Recently this bill passed both chambers of Congress and was signed into law on March 23, 2018. The [[65th Infantry Regiment (United States)|Borinqueneers]] were a U.S Army segregated unit of Puerto Ricans who fought in WWI, WWII and Korean War with great distinction and valor. In 2014, they were honored with the Congressional Gold Medal for their brave service to our country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/4042/amendments|title=Amendments - H.R.4042 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): To designate the facility of the United States Postal Service located at 1415 West Oak Street, in Kissimmee, Florida, as the \"Borinqueneers Post Office Building\".|first=Soto,|last=Darren|date=March 23, 2018|website=www.congress.gov|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCongressman Soto passed a law to protect billfish, such as marlin, spearfish, and sailfish. H.R. 4528 closes a loophole in the Billfish Conservation Act making it illegal to sell billfish in the continental United States. The law passed the U.S. House on June 25, 2018 and was signed into law on August 2, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.floridasportsman.com/2018/08/13/new-law-prohibits-sale-billfish-united-states/ |title=New Law Prohibits Sale of Billfish in United States |publisher=Florida Sportsman |date=August 13, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Commodity Exchanges, Energy, and Credit|Subcommittee on Commodity Exchanges, Energy, and Credit]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Nutrition|Subcommittee on Nutrition]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources|Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Indian, Insular and Alaska Native Affairs|Subcommittee on Indian, Insular and Alaska Native Affairs]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n===Caucuses===\n* '''[[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Caucus Members|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|accessdate=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* '''[[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members |url=https://congressionalhispaniccaucus-lujangrisham.house.gov/members|publisher=Congressional Hispanic Caucus|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n===Immigration===\nSoto is a staunch advocate for DREAMers and is working with fellow members of the Hispanic Caucus to pass the DREAM Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/opinion/columns/column-dreamers-represent-american-values/2336312|title=Column:|date=September 5, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In June 2018, Congressman Soto traveled to Homestead, Florida to tour a detention facility with several Democratic Members of Congress where he argued against Trump's zero tolerance policy and the separation of children and families.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/06/23/wasserman-schultz-two-more-south-florida-facilities-holding-children-separated-from-their-families/ |title=Wasserman Schultz: Two more South Florida facilities holding children separated from their families. &#124; Tampa Bay Times |publisher=Tampabay.com |date=June 23, 2018 |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref> He has been the strongest advocate in Congress for Alejandra Juarez, the wife of an Iraq combat veteran and mother of two American daughters, who was deported to Mexico recently due to Trump's zero tolerance policy. \"Zero tolerance literally ripped this family apart,\" said Rep. Darren Soto \"The administration is so extreme on immigration that they\u2019re deporting the spouses of military veterans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/this-veteran-supported-trump-until-trump-deported-his-wife/2018/08/06/33083252-99bc-11e8-b60b-1c897f17e185_story.html?noredirect=on&utm_term=.bc6f2fdca517 |title=When a Trump supporter\u2019s wife is deported |publisher=The Washington Post |date= |accessdate=September 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Environmental Policy===\nDarren is officially the greenest Member of the Florida Congressional Delegation for 2017. He received a perfect score of 100 for his environmental issues voting record from the National League of Conservation Voters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/257821-darren-soto-gets-perfect-score-conservation-voters-tops-florida-members|title=Darren Soto gets perfect score from Conservation Voters, tops Florida members|date=March 1, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> He introduced the Wild and Scenic River Study Act of 2017 (H.R.3961), which passed unanimously out of committee on January 17, 2018. On April 16, 2018, this bill passed unanimously out of the U.S. House.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunshinestatenews.com/story/darren-sotos-bill-protecting-kissimmee-river-clears-house-without-opposition|title=Darren Soto's Bill Protecting Kissimmee River Clears House Without Opposition|date=April 17, 2018|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> Soto led strong opposition to Trump Administration proposals to permit oil drilling off Florida's Gulf and Atlantic coasts during the House Committee on Natural Resources meetings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/ryan-zinke-offshore-drilling-florida-darren-soto_us_5a620bf1e4b0125fd63618c0|title=Florida Waters Could Still Be Leased For Oil Drilling, Despite Ryan Zinke\u2019s Tweet|first=Chris|last=D'Angelo|date=January 19, 2018|accessdate=July 4, 2018|via=Huff Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridapolitics.com/archives/240545-darren-soto-pins-everglades-drilling-assurances-interior-secretary|title=Darren Soto pins down Everglades, drilling assurances from interior secretary - Florida Politics|website=floridapolitics.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://orlando-politics.com/2017/07/20/rep-soto-opposes-oil-drilling-seismic-testing-in-remarks-to-natural-resources-committee/|title=Rep. Soto Opposes Oil Drilling, Seismic Testing, in Remarks to Natural Resources Committee|last=Conroy |first=Cathy |date=July 20, 2017 |website=orlando-politics.com |publisher=Political Observer}}</ref> Soto has also championed funding increases for the National Estuary Program the National Wildlife Refuge System program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tampabay.com/opinion/columns/Column-Congress-should-find-money-to-support-estuaries-in-Tampa-Bay-Florida_162070773|title=Column: Congress should find money to support estuaries in Tampa Bay, Florida|date=October 27, 2017|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 6, 2018, Soto passed his Shark and Billfish Protection Act out of House Natural Resources Committee. Senator Bill Nelson passed the Senate companion bill on October 2, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportfishingpolicy.com/media-room/angler-backed-billfish-conservation-act-clears-u-s-house-natural-resources-committee/|title=Center for Sportfishing Policy |website=www.sportfishingpolicy.com|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Gun control===\n\nSoto received an \"A\" rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] in 2012,<ref name=\"Schneider 2015\">{{cite news |last=Schneider |first= Elena|date=December 15, 2015 |title=Gun control becomes a litmus test in Democratic primaries |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2015/12/gun-control-democratic-primaries-nra-216764 |work=Politico |location=Arlington County, Virginia |access-date=March 1, 2018 }}</ref> but his views on the Second Amendment changed after the 2012 Newtown Shooting. In the Florida Senate, he became a reliable vote for gun safety, which ultimately led to earning a \"D\" rating from the NRA for his service there from 2013-2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/os-congress-darren-soto-profile-20161202-story.html|title=Entering GOP-led Congress, Democrat Soto no stranger to being outnumbered|first=Jeff|last=Weiner|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the Pulse tragedy, Soto called for a special session to prevent those on the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI's]] [[No Fly List]] from purchasing firearms.<ref name=\"Rohrer 2016\">{{cite news |last=Rohrer |first=Gray |date=June 17, 2016 |title=GOP, Democrats still battle over gun control in Florida |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/pulse-orlando-nightclub-shooting/politics/os-orlando-shooting-gun-control-legislature-20160617-story.html |work=Orlando Sentinel |location=Orlando, Florida |access-date=March 1, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nSince 2017 to present, he has been a reliable vote for gun safety reform. After the February 2018 Marjorie Stoneman Douglas High School Shooting, he proposed his \"Gun Safety Action Plan.\" He listed five steps: universal background checks for gun purchases, keeping guns away from those who are a danger to themselves or others, banning assault weapons and bump stocks, creating a \"red-flag\" system to issue gun restraining orders, and disallowing anyone on the federal terrorism \"no-fly\" list from buying a gun.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theledger.com/news/20180226/polk-lawmakers-seek-gun-law-changes-but-differ-on-details|title=Polk lawmakers seek gun law changes, but differ on details|first=Gary|last=White |accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]] in Florida in 2018, Soto stated that gun control will be \"one of those litmus test issues\" in the [[United States elections, 2018|2018 midterms]].<ref name=\"Cheddar 2018\">{{cite web |url=https://cheddar.com/videos/florida-rep-darren-soto-gun-reform-will-be-a-litmus-test-at-the-midterms |title=Florida Rep. Darren Soto: Gun Reform Will Be a \"Litmus Test\" at the Midterms |date=February 28, 2018 |website=Cheddar |publisher=Cheddar, Inc. |access-date=March 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Hurricane safety===\nWorking with Senator Bill Nelson, Soto passed his first law in Congress on April 18, 2017 creating a backup fleet of hurricane hunter aircraft to monitor hurricanes affecting Florida and other nearby areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://orlando-politics.com/2017/04/05/darren-soto-applauds-passage-of-hurricane-hunter-back-up-bill/|title=Darren Soto applauds passage of Hurricane Hunter Aircraft back-up bill|last=Torres |first=Frank |date= April 5, 2017|website=orlando-politics.com |publisher=Political Observer}}</ref>\n\n===Recovery assistance===\nSoto is working on debt reduction and tax, healthcare, agriculture and small business relief to assist Puerto Rico in its economic recovery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/opinion/front-burner/os-ed-renegotiate-puerto-rico-debt-front-burner-20170509-story.html|title=Darren Soto: Give power back to people of Puerto Rico|first=Darren |last=Soto|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> He also successfully led a bipartisan letter requesting FEMA Designation of Individual Assistance for the citizens of Orange, Osceola, Polk, Lake and Seminole counties after Hurricane Irma.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/weather/hurricane/os-hurricane-irma-damage-orange-20170912-story.html|title=Trump approves greater FEMA aid for 37 Florida counties|first=Mary |last=Shanklin |accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, he voted to bring back billions of dollars in recovery funding to Central Florida and Puerto Rico following Hurricanes Irma and Maria.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nOn April 1, 2018, Soto's wife, Amanda Soto, was arrested at Walt Disney World and charged with disorderly intoxication. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Ruiz |first1=Stephen |last2=Lemongello |first2=Steven |title=Congressman Darren Soto's wife arrested at Walt Disney World |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-darren-soto-wife-arrested-0402-story.html |website=Orlando Sentinel |accessdate=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement, Darren Soto said his wife had been in treatment for depression for years and had recently stopped taking medication in accordance with her treatment plan and under her doctor's supervision. He went on to say that \"she deeply regrets her actions and takes full responsibility for them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/politics/political-pulse/os-darren-soto-wife-arrested-0402-story.html|title=Congressman Darren Soto's wife arrested at Walt Disney World |first=Stephen Ruiz, Steven|last=Lemongello|accessdate=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Hispanic Americans in the United States Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://soto.house.gov Congressman Darren Soto] official U.S. House website\n* [https://www.darrensoto.com/ Campaign website]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Florida/Government/Federal/US_House/Darren_Soto_%5BD-9%5D}}\n* {{ CongLinks | congbio = S001200 | fec = H6FL09179 | votesmart = 67618 | congress = darren-soto/S001200 }}\n* {{C-SPAN|da